  "prompt": "How do pulse oximeters work?",
  "response": "Pulse oximeters work by measuring the oxygen saturation of hemoglobin in the blood using light absorption principles. Here's a detailed explanation:\n\n1. Basic mechanism:\n- A pulse oximeter clips onto a body part (usually a fingertip or earlobe)\n- It contains two light-emitting diodes (LEDs) that shine light through the tissue\n- One LED emits red light, the other infrared light\n\n2. Light absorption process:\n- Oxygenated hemoglobin absorbs more infrared light\n- Deoxygenated hemoglobin absorbs more red light\n- The device measures the difference in light absorption\n\n3. Calculation steps:\n- Compares the amount of red and infrared light that passes through the tissue\n- Calculates the ratio of oxygenated to total hemoglobin\n- Displays oxygen saturation as a percentage (SpO2)\n\n4. Additional features:\n- Also measures pulse rate by detecting blood flow pulses\n- Uses photodetectors to measure light passing through the tissue\n- Electronic circuits process the light absorption data\n\n5. Typical uses:\n- Medical monitoring\n- Sleep studies\n- High altitude activities\n- Respiratory condition management\n\nThe device provides a non-invasive way to quickly assess blood oxygen levels.",
